Bringing in the New Year with intention, quality relationships and an open heart. Happy New Year friends 💃🏻🙏🏼

Grateful for another year of LIFE!! Grateful for my friends and family, grateful for my physical and mental health, and SO excited for what this new chapter has in store for me!

Building a life I don’t have to escape from is one of the most beautiful gifts I have given myself for my birthday. With every new birthday year, brings growth, lessons and memories I will never take for granted 🙏🏼❤️.

Thank you all for the birthday wishes and cheers to MORE LIFE💃🏻🥂
Beyond blessed ❤️🙏🏼🎂

My biggest advice for women entering a male dominated work force:

1. Stay true to your values even when it feels like sacrificing them could get you ahead.
2. If you put in the work, KNOW that you belong in that room! 
3. Surround yourself with other goal oriented, like minded-women. Support is everything. 
4. Stay humble. No job is secure and you can be replaced at any moment.
5. Speak your mind. Don’t let anyone diminish your voice.
6. Keep learning! Knowledge is power! 
7. Be adaptable to change! Life is constantly evolving. Embrace it. 
8. Lead with LOVE!
9. Be vulnerable and willing to make mistakes. That’s a normal part of growth. You don’t have to be perfect all the time!
10. Have a work/life balance! Don’t be so focused on making a living that you forget to live.
I won’t be remembered as a woman who keeps her mouth shut and I’m okay with that 😆🫶🏼

The 3 steps I took to get what I wanted in sports:

1. Wrote down my goals, the sacrifices I had to make everyday to get those goals, who I had to work and network with, and what skills I had to acquire to achieve my goals.

2. Applied what I wrote down to my everyday life and held myself ACCOUNTABLE!.

3. Positive mindset. Even through all the No’s and all the ups and downs in life, you gotta stay after it. Can’t knock down a door? Build your own door to walk through. Can’t find a seat at the table? Find a different table or build your own damn table!

In order to go places you’ve never been, you must do things you’ve never done. Society likes to put us in a box and make us feel that we have to follow the traditional route to achieve success. Don’t be afraid to create your own lane and ask for help along the way 🙏🏼❤️

Sometimes the worst place you can be is in your own head. I know we’ve all been there. And I’m here to tell you… IT’S OKAY to have moments of self-doubt and negative thoughts. You’re human. But what are you doing to channel those thoughts in a positive way? Thoughts come and go. It’s what you do with those thoughts that matter. 

Don’t be the reason you can’t move forward. Do what scares you. Do what challenges you. Start that podcast. Start that business. Start that workout routine. All it takes is EFFORT. The results will come.

I’ve lost 20 pounds in the past 3-4 months or so and have noticed a complete change in my body structure. Eating clean consistently, lots of walking, heavy lifting, sprints, yoga, lots of sunlight, and NO alcohol. 

What I’m most proud of is honoring the process, being my own nutritionist, my own trainer, and my own motivator. I got sick of my own shit and made a promise to myself to stay committed to my goals.

It doesn’t matter how old you are. It’s never too late to get started again. I was legit feeling so miserable a few months ago. I couldn’t fit in my clothes, it hurt to tie my shoes, everything hurt and every time I would eat I would get sick. I thought to myself, “I can’t function like this anymore. This isn’t the life I imagined for myself.” So I stopped making excuses, wrote up a plan and stay locked in.

I used to be one of those girls who was overdoing cardio… 1-2 hours a day like a crazy person… depleting any muscle I had left and actually doing the opposite of my intentions in the gym. I was gaining weight and not losing any fat. Now, I’m lifting 5-6 days per week, sprinting 2-3 days per week and doing a steady state walk or stair master 1-2 days per week for no more than 30 minutes.

My diet is still pretty strict although I allow myself a few cheats throughout the week.

There’s a version of yourself you haven’t met yet. Keep showing up until you’re introduced.

📸 @dgamboaaa

My platform has always been about giving the athlete a voice… 

And we can’t, as a society, claim to care about our first amendment right if we want to censor athletes from using their platforms to speak on issues they care about, and as much as I may disagree on some viewpoints, I also respect their opinion and try to understand where they’re coming from.

It all comes back to empathy. I just ask that the same empathy is given in return.

Moral of the story: stay true to yourself no matter what industry you’re in. This was just one element in the life of a female reporter being told how to look and what to wear even if it meant stepping outside my boundaries to appease others. Somethings I agreed with changing, others I chose not to.

Regardless, you’re a product of the choices you make. Some may be good. Some may be bad. But in the end it’s all a learning experience. I chased perfection for so long only to realize I’ll never be perfect and that’s ok 😊
Made you look 😉
